Author: actionslacks#4072
Content: It's a bit like comparing apples and oranges at this point. Considering all the new things going on here, we could start our own commit tracking just comparing projects within this ecosystem.

Author: Regnar#6164
Content: Or if we simply start our own git tracking, show what we are tracking and why, and how we compiled them all to get the end result. we can set the standard for other projects to show their own work

Author: bpkdasbaum#4592
Content: Setting new standards is always tricky, because it just adds another level. I was concerned originally that when people try to find and compare coins with high activity, and look at KMD, when on crypto miso it appears as if KMD is dead, although that's not the case. Ideally we'd have something that can be visible / shared on third party sites. So when people do compare to other projects, they see that KMD is active.

Author: bpkdasbaum#4592
Content: I see activity in general in high regard. Be it wallets, transactions or in this case github commits.

Author: bpkdasbaum#4592
Content: I think more ppl do this and it would spark more interest from ppl who don't know the project yet, bring more ppl in

Author: bpkdasbaum#4592
Content: Only need to create visibility for it that can also be used by third party sites. If it was for example only on the kmd website, it would only reach ppl who are already interested in KMD and visit the site to find out more. But if we show up on comparison sites like blocktivity and also get high scores there, then this brings ppl in who haven't even looked into KMD yet

Content: as far as diy tracking we should also include all the outside projects using dpow

Content: I agree it would be nice to get an unbiased analysis from outside sites but I'm not gonna hold my breath

Author: Regnar#6164
Content: I was trying to indicate that if we track ourselves, and show exactly how/where we are tracking and why, we could see if third party sites will just mirror our tracking method.

Author: Regnar#6164
Content: Which means if we track a repo, we need to explain and show how that repo is related to KMD development. which right now a lot of KMD development is done through other Repos like Staked, KMDice, etc. and then there's also development that is technically third party but is on run time forks and can be brought back to KMD like Veruscoin (though this stuff shouldn't be tracked) it's a tricky situation but it's also the nature of a truly decentralized project. clarity is key

Author: actionslacks#4072
Content: I agree. sorry to insert my skepticism into the conversation. There are so many people doing so many things here that a complete and accurate analysis would be a task in itself. Which I think is wonderful.

Author: Regnar#6164
Content: Oh @actionslacks I didn't take your statement as skepticism, nor is it a bad thing if it was! haha skepticism is good in crypto! yea it's tough to get an accurate gauge of the development being done, or trusting self reporting, which is why I was saying we openly show what we are tracking and why, so others can verify it.
